ench <i>viniter</i>, <i>vinter</i> ‘wine merchant’.","Irish: Anglicized form (part translation) of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla-Gheimhridh</b> ‘son of the lad of winter’, from <i>geimhreadh</i> ‘winter’. This name is also Anglicized <b>McAlivery</b>."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Wyntour was born in 1160, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Jenkin Wyntour, was 30 and his mother, Angharad verch Philip of Wales, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Jane Morgan. He died in 1240, in his hometown, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1160–1240":"1160–1240","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1164–1225":"1164–1225","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1196–Male":"1196–Surnud","1130–1215":"1130–1215","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1250":"1250","1194":"1194","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"